.TH "pcpu_page_first_chunk" 9 "pcpu_page_first_chunk" "May 2021" "Kernel Hacker's Manual" LINUX
.SH NAME
pcpu_page_first_chunk \- map the first chunk using PAGE_SIZE pages
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B "int" pcpu_page_first_chunk
.BI "(size_t reserved_size "  ","
.BI "pcpu_fc_alloc_fn_t alloc_fn "  ","
.BI "pcpu_fc_free_fn_t free_fn "  ","
.BI "pcpu_fc_populate_pte_fn_t populate_pte_fn "  ");"
.SH ARGUMENTS
.IP "reserved_size" 12
the size of reserved percpu area in bytes
.IP "alloc_fn" 12
function to allocate percpu page, always called with PAGE_SIZE
.IP "free_fn" 12
function to free percpu page, always called with PAGE_SIZE
.IP "populate_pte_fn" 12
function to populate pte
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
This is a helper to ease setting up page-remapped first percpu
chunk and can be called where \fBpcpu_setup_first_chunk\fP is expected.

This is the basic allocator.  Static percpu area is allocated
page-by-page into vmalloc area.
.SH "RETURN"
0 on success, -errno on failure.
